## Best Practices from Industry Leaders

### Stripe Documentation (Industry Standard)

**What makes Stripe docs great:**
- ✅ **Progressive disclosure**: Quickstart → Guide → Reference
- ✅ **Interactive examples**: "Try it" sections with copy-paste code
- ✅ **Use-case organization**: Docs organized by what you're trying to do
- ✅ **Complete examples**: Every example is runnable and complete

**Apply to MaiaOS:**
- Start with quickstart examples
- Show complete, runnable MaiaScript examples
- Organize by use case ("Creating a todo app" not "CoMap API")
- Include "Try it yourself" sections

### MDN Web Docs (Mozilla)

**What makes MDN great:**
- ✅ **Clear structure**: Overview → Syntax → Examples → Specifications
- ✅ **Multiple examples**: Basic → Intermediate → Advanced
- ✅ **Accessibility**: Clear language, good formatting
- ✅ **Interactive**: Code examples you can edit

**Apply to MaiaOS:**
- Follow consistent structure across all docs
- Provide examples at multiple complexity levels
- Use clear formatting (code blocks, callouts, diagrams)
- Make examples copy-paste ready

### React Documentation

**What makes React docs great:**
- ✅ **Conceptual first**: Explains "why" before "how"
- ✅ **Practical examples**: Real-world scenarios
- ✅ **Progressive tutorials**: Build understanding step-by-step
- ✅ **Common mistakes**: Shows what NOT to do

**Apply to MaiaOS:**
- Explain why MaiaOS works the way it does
- Use real-world examples (todo apps, blogs, etc.)
- Build tutorials that progress logically
- Include "Common Pitfalls" sections

